Detects circular *module* dependencies within a crate (as opposed to circular crate dependencies, which Cargo already rejects). Invoked as a standalone check script, likely from CI or a pre-commit hook, not from Rust code.

Requires the external `cargo-modules` subcommand to be installed (`cargo install cargo-modules`); exits 1 immediately with an install hint if missing. Runs `cargo modules dependencies --lib --no-externs --no-sysroot --no-uses` and fails if that command errors. Despite the file's stated purpose, actual cycle detection is **not implemented** — the script only verifies `cargo-modules` runs cleanly and prints a `NOTE:` to stderr saying so; it never parses the DOT/graph output for cycles. Anyone relying on this script to actually catch a cycle will get a false pass.

Real cycle detection is deferred to "dylint rule 4," referenced via `docs/DYLINT_RULES.md` — that doc is the source of truth for the planned replacement, and this script is expected to be superseded once that rule exists.

The `--lib` flag is required because the crate also has binary targets, which would otherwise make target selection ambiguous. Comment block mentions `--no-fns --no-types --no-traits` as desirable but notes current cargo-modules versions vary in support, so they're not actually passed. Uses `set -euo pipefail`; `FAIL` variable and final `exit $FAIL` exist as scaffolding for future logic but currently `FAIL=1` only gets set on the cargo-modules invocation failing, not on any cycle finding.